    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-05-15T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-05-15T06:00:00-05:00" n="575"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d575">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00112 European War 1939/5507: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé at Tangier</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Childs</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tangier</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-05-15T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 15, 1942—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 6:41 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>221. My 195, May 5, 8 p.m. I informed General Orgaz yesterday when he lunched at
                    the Legation that I had received his note of April 30 and had forwarded it to
                    Washington and would let him know as soon as a reply was received.</p>
                <p>He stated he was coming to Tangier in June to spend the summer here when he would
                    have the opportunity of relinquishing some of his responsibility to his
                    subordinates in whom he has great confidence. He would then have an opportunity
                    of discussing directly with me these matters of mutual interest.</p>
                <p>He, General Mugica, Secretary General of the Spanish Zone, and General Uriarte,
                    delegate in Tangier of the High Commissioner, were shown selections of
                    photographs of the American production effort which greatly impressed them.
                    Uriarte commented, “This is the finest kind of propaganda.”</p>
                <p>Repeated to Madrid.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Childs</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
